				<p>
				</p><ul>
					<li><strong>Download Widget - Calendar-Widget is outside of viewing area</strong><br>
					<ul>
						<li>Modern Browsers provide the possibility to Zoom In &amp; Out (e.g to increase the readability). This feature, usually activated by using a combination of the Ctrl/Strg-Key plus the + or - Key or by using the Ctrl/Strg-Key plus the Mouse-Wheel, changes the total viewable screen-size, which results in a change of the corresponding sizes of the widgets. This causes the Calendar-Widget to be outside the viewing area. To resolve this problem, please use one of the these Key combinations (Ctrl/Strg-Key plus the + or - Key or the Ctrl/Strg-Key plus the Mouse-Wheel) to Zoom Out again, until the Calendar-Widget is fully visible again. If you use the Mouse-Wheel, please make sure that you first position your Mouse-Pointer at the CryoLand-Menu-Bar (located at the top), since only the Map will be zoomed if the Mouse-Pointer is located inside the Map-Window.  If none of the described Key combinations work, please consult the Help of your Browser for further information.</li>
					</ul>
					</li>
					<br>

					<li><strong>Fast access to a certain Date</strong><br>
					<ol>
						<li>By Selecting a Date: The Download-Widget provides Start and End Date-Fields. Please use the Calendar-Widget to select the desired Date value. Especially the Start Date-Field can be used to jump around fast i.e. to directly jump to a certain Date. Please make sure that the End-Date is after the Start-Date, and correct it if necessary (otherwise this feature will not work). </li>
						<li>Using the Time-Slider: the Time-Slider provides Fast-Forward and a Fast-Backward buttons (on the left and right end), to ease access to irregular products or to skip over prolonged periods (e.g. non-snow season). The Time-Slider will jump to the next Date with a selected product available.</li>
					</ol>
					</li>
					<br>

					<li><strong>When selecting a dataset, some areas on the map are shown in pink</strong><br>
					<ul>
						<li>If the CryoLand server can't deliver fast enough (e.g. due to current load) it runs into a timeout, which results in these pink tiles - which represent tiles which got not delivered. Mostly a full reload (using Ctrl+R or Ctrl+F5) should overcome this. Sometimes even a shift/pan of the viewing area is enough to reload these tiles.  But sometimes, unfortunately, the browser will only contact its local Cache and is not issuing a real reload. Therefore the first method is the recommended one.</li>
					</ul>
					</li>
					<br>
					
					<li><strong>Why is it needed to confirm every downloaded coverage</strong><br>
					<ul>
						<li>The requirement to to confirm every downloaded file separately comes from the browsers side. We do´t have any influence on this. <br>
						However, for the download of larger series we recommend the use of a script (e.g see the ones provided by CryoLand → Help section "Integration and Automation"). Please consult this "Integration and Automation" section for more detailed information. In case you need further help with scripting or have special needs please feel free to contact us. The contact information is provided at the end of this FAQ.</li>
					</ul>
					</li>
					<br>

					<li><strong>The downloaded files have a strange filename</strong><br>
					<ul>
						<li>Filename example: "SWE_0.1deg_201304040000_SSMIS_PanEurope_FMIV1.0.tif_20131107071245.tif". When downloading coverages it would be possible to donwload different AOIs from the same base-coverage (with the same filename). In order to ensure we don't overwrite already downloaded files, (e.g. during script-based automatic downloads), we extend the downloaded filename with the timestamp of the download and again with its respective extensions. So in the above example the  "_20131107071245.tif" ending of the filename is added during the download to ensure uniqueness and of the filename and prevent accidentally overwriting of files coming from the same source coverage.</li>
					</ul>
					</li>
